The paper discusses an empirical study on the behavior of an optimization method (MAX-MIN Ant System) in a fuzzy environment. This involves the use of heuristic methods to solve an optimization problem derived from the Traveling Salesman Problem (TSP). The study involves testing several publicly-available symmetric TSP instances and their fuzzy variants. The paper also proposes a two-dimensional systematic degree of fuzziness to adapt the entry data. Based on this, the most likely arXiv CS sub-categories are cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) and cs.NE (Neural and Evolutionary Computing) as the paper discusses the use of heuristic methods and optimization algorithms. The paper also involves testing and analyzing data, which makes cs.DM (Data Mining) a likely sub-category. The paper also discusses the resilience and adaptability of the proposed method, which makes cs.SY (Systems and Control) a possible sub-category. Finally, the paper involves empirical study and analysis, which makes cs.LG (Machine Learning) a possible sub-category.
